[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] In statistics and machine learning, the **bias–variance tradeoff** describes the relationship between a model's complexity, the accuracy of its predictions, and how well it can make predictions on previously unseen data that were not used to train the model.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] In general, as the number of tunable parameters in a model increases, it becomes more flexible, and can better fit a training data set.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] That is, the model has lower error or lower bias.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] However, for more flexible models, there will tend to be greater **variance** to the model fit each time we take a set of samples to create a new training data set.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] It is said that there is greater variance in the model's estimated parameters.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] The **bias–variance decomposition** is a way of analyzing a learning algorithm's expected generalization error with respect to a particular problem as a sum of three terms, the bias, variance, and a quantity called the *irreducible error*, resulting from noise in the problem itself.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] For each trial, a few noisy data points are provided as a training set (top).
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] For a wide spread (image 2) the bias is high: the RBFs cannot fully approximate the function (especially the central dip), but the variance between different trials is low.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] As spread decreases (image 3 and 4) the bias decreases: the blue curves more closely approximate the red.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] However, depending on the noise in different trials the variance between trials increases.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] In the lowermost image the approximated values for x=0 varies wildly depending on where the data points were located.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] The bias–variance tradeoff is a central problem in supervised learning.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] Ideally, one wants to choose a model that both accurately captures the regularities in its training data, but also generalizes well to unseen data.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] Unfortunately, it is typically impossible to do both simultaneously.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] High-variance learning methods may be able to represent their training set well but are at risk of overfitting to noisy or unrepresentative training data.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] In contrast, algorithms with high bias typically produce simpler models that may fail to capture important regularities (i.e. underfit) in the data.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] It is an often made fallacy to assume that complex models must have high variance.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] High variance models are "complex" in some sense, but the reverse need not be true.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] In addition, one has to be careful how to define complexity.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] In particular, the number of parameters used to describe the model is a poor measure of complexity.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] The model $f_{a,b}(x)=a\sin(bx)$ has only two parameters ( $a,b$ ) but it can interpolate any number of points by oscillating with a high enough frequency, resulting in both a high bias and high variance.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] An analogy can be made to the relationship between accuracy and precision.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] Accuracy is one way of quantifying bias and can intuitively be improved by selecting from only local information.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] Consequently, a sample will appear accurate (i.e. have low bias) under the aforementioned selection conditions, but may result in underfitting.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] In other words, test data may not agree as closely with training data, which would indicate imprecision and therefore inflated variance.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] A graphical example would be a straight line fit to data exhibiting quadratic behavior overall.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] Precision is a description of variance and generally can only be improved by selecting information from a comparatively larger space.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] The option to select many data points over a broad sample space is the ideal condition for any analysis.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] However, intrinsic constraints (whether physical, theoretical, computational, etc.) will always play a limiting role.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] The limiting case where only a finite number of data points are selected over a broad sample space may result in improved precision and lower variance overall, but may also result in an overreliance on the training data (overfitting).
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] This means that test data would also not agree as closely with the training data, but in this case the reason is inaccuracy or high bias.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] To borrow from the previous example, the graphical representation would appear as a high-order polynomial fit to the same data exhibiting quadratic behavior.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] Note that error in each case is measured the same way, but the reason ascribed to the error is different depending on the balance between bias and variance.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] To mitigate how much information is used from neighboring observations, a model can be smoothed via explicit regularization, such as shrinkage.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] Suppose that we have a training set consisting of a set of points $x_{1},\dots ,x_{n}$ and real-valued labels $y_{i}$ associated with the points $x_{i}$ .
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] We assume that the data is generated by a function $f(x)$ such as $y=f(x)+\varepsilon$ , where the noise, $\varepsilon$ , has zero mean and unit variance $\sigma ^{2}$ .
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] We want to find a function ${\hat {f}}\!(x;D)$ , that approximates the true function $f(x)$ as well as possible, by means of some learning algorithm based on a training dataset (sample) $D=\{(x_{1},y_{1})\dots ,(x_{n},y_{n})\}$ .
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] We make "as well as possible" precise by measuring the mean squared error between y and ${\hat {f}}\!(x;D)$ : we want $(y-{\hat {f}}\!(x;D))^{2}$ to be minimal, both for $x_{1},\dots ,x_{n}$ *and for points outside of our sample*.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] Of course, we cannot hope to do so perfectly, since the $y_{i}$ contain noise $\varepsilon$ ; this means we must be prepared to accept an *irreducible error* in any function we come up with.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] Finding an ${\hat {f}}$ that generalizes to points outside of the training set can be done with any of the countless algorithms used for supervised learning.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] The expectation ranges over different choices of the training set $D=\{(x_{1},y_{1})\dots ,(x_{n},y_{n})\}$ , all sampled from the same joint distribution $P(x,y)$ which can for example be done via bootstrapping.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] Since all three terms are non-negative, the irreducible error forms a lower bound on the expected error on unseen samples.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] The more complex the model ${\hat {f}}\!(x)$ is, the more data points it will capture, and the lower the bias will be.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] However, complexity will make the model "move" more to capture the data points, and hence its variance will be larger.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] The derivation of the bias–variance decomposition for squared error proceeds as follows.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] For convenience, we drop the D subscript in the following lines, such that ${\hat {f}}\!(x;D)={\hat {f}}\!(x)$ .
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] Moreover, the third term of this equation is nothing but $\sigma ^{2}$ , the variance of $\varepsilon$ .
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] This last series of equalities comes from the fact that $f(x)$ is not a random variable, but a fixed, deterministic function of x .
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] Dimensionality reduction and feature selection can decrease variance by simplifying models.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] Similarly, a larger training set tends to decrease variance.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] Adding features (predictors) tends to decrease bias, at the expense of introducing additional variance.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] One way of resolving the trade-off is to use mixture models and ensemble learning.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] For example, boosting combines many "weak" (high bias) models in an ensemble that has lower bias than the individual models, while bagging combines "strong" learners in a way that reduces their variance.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] Model validation methods such as cross-validation (statistics) can be used to tune models so as to optimize the trade-off.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] where $N_{1}(x),\dots ,N_{k}(x)$ are the k nearest neighbors of x in the training set.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] The bias (first term) is a monotone rising function of k, while the variance (second term) drops off as k is increased.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] In fact, under "reasonable assumptions" the bias of the first-nearest neighbor (1-NN) estimator vanishes entirely as the size of the training set approaches infinity.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] The bias–variance decomposition forms the conceptual basis for regression regularization methods such as LASSO and ridge regression.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] Regularization methods introduce bias into the regression solution that can reduce variance considerably relative to the ordinary least squares (OLS) solution.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] Although the OLS solution provides non-biased regression estimates, the lower variance solutions produced by regularization techniques provide superior MSE performance.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] The bias–variance decomposition was originally formulated for least-squares regression.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] For the case of classification under the 0-1 loss (misclassification rate), it is possible to find a similar decomposition, with the caveat that the variance term becomes dependent on the target label.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] Alternatively, if the classification problem can be phrased as probabilistic classification, then the expected cross-entropy can instead be decomposed to give bias and variance terms with the same semantics but taking a different form.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] Even though the bias–variance decomposition does not directly apply in reinforcement learning, a similar tradeoff can also characterize generalization.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] When an agent has limited information on its environment, the suboptimality of an RL algorithm can be decomposed into the sum of two terms: a term related to an asymptotic bias and a term due to overfitting.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] The asymptotic bias is directly related to the learning algorithm (independently of the quantity of data) while the overfitting term comes from the fact that the amount of data is limited.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] While in traditional Monte Carlo methods the bias is typically zero, modern approaches, such as Markov chain Monte Carlo are only asymptotically unbiased, at best.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] While widely discussed in the context of machine learning, the bias–variance dilemma has been examined in the context of human cognition, most notably by Gerd Gigerenzer and co-workers in the context of learned heuristics.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] They have argued (see references below) that the human brain resolves the dilemma in the case of the typically sparse, poorly-characterized training-sets provided by experience by adopting high-bias/low variance heuristics.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] This reflects the fact that a zero-bias approach has poor generalizability to new situations, and also unreasonably presumes precise knowledge of the true state of the world.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] The resulting heuristics are relatively simple, but produce better inferences in a wider variety of situations.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] Geman et al. argue that the bias–variance dilemma implies that abilities such as generic object recognition cannot be learned from scratch, but require a certain degree of "hard wiring" that is later tuned by experience.
[src:computational-learning/bias-variance-tradeoff] This is because model-free approaches to inference require impractically large training sets if they are to avoid high variance.
[src:computational-learning/computational-learning-theory] In computer science, **computational learning theory** (or just **learning theory**) is a subfield of artificial intelligence devoted to studying the design and analysis of machine learning algorithms.
[src:computational-learning/computational-learning-theory] Theoretical results in machine learning often focus on a type of inductive learning known as supervised learning.
[src:computational-learning/computational-learning-theory] In supervised learning, an algorithm is provided with labeled samples.
[src:computational-learning/computational-learning-theory] For instance, the samples might be descriptions of mushrooms, with labels indicating whether they are edible or not.
[src:computational-learning/computational-learning-theory] The algorithm uses these labeled samples to create a classifier.
[src:computational-learning/computational-learning-theory] This classifier assigns labels to new samples, including those it has not previously encountered.
[src:computational-learning/computational-learning-theory] The goal of the supervised learning algorithm is to optimize performance metrics, such as minimizing errors on new samples.
[src:computational-learning/computational-learning-theory] In addition to performance bounds, computational learning theory studies the time complexity and feasibility of learning.
[src:computational-learning/computational-learning-theory] In computational learning theory, a computation is considered feasible if it can be done in polynomial time.
[src:computational-learning/computational-learning-theory] There are several different approaches to computational learning theory based on making different assumptions about the inference principles used to generalise from limited data.
[src:computational-learning/computational-learning-theory] This includes different definitions of probability (see frequency probability, Bayesian probability) and different assumptions on the generation of samples.
[src:computational-learning/computational-learning-theory] While its primary goal is to understand learning abstractly, computational learning theory has led to the development of practical algorithms.
[src:computational-learning/computational-learning-theory] For example, PAC theory inspired boosting, VC theory led to support vector machines, and Bayesian inference led to belief networks.
[src:computational-learning/statistical-learning-theory] The goals of learning are understanding and prediction.
[src:computational-learning/statistical-learning-theory] Learning falls into many categories, including supervised learning, unsupervised learning, online learning, and reinforcement learning.
[src:computational-learning/statistical-learning-theory] From the perspective of statistical learning theory, supervised learning is best understood.
[src:computational-learning/statistical-learning-theory] Supervised learning involves learning from a training set of data.
[src:computational-learning/statistical-learning-theory] Every point in the training is an input–output pair, where the input maps to an output.
[src:computational-learning/statistical-learning-theory] The learning problem consists of inferring the function that maps between the input and the output, such that the learned function can be used to predict the output from future input.
[src:computational-learning/statistical-learning-theory] Depending on the type of output, supervised learning problems are either problems of regression or problems of classification.
[src:computational-learning/statistical-learning-theory] If the output takes a continuous range of values, it is a regression problem.
[src:computational-learning/statistical-learning-theory] Using Ohm's law as an example, a regression could be performed with voltage as input and current as an output.
[src:computational-learning/statistical-learning-theory] The regression would find the functional relationship between voltage and current to be R , such that $V=IR$ Classification problems are those for which the output will be an element from a discrete set of labels.
[src:computational-learning/statistical-learning-theory] Classification is very common for machine learning applications.
[src:computational-learning/statistical-learning-theory] In facial recognition, for instance, a picture of a person's face would be the input, and the output label would be that person's name.
[src:computational-learning/statistical-learning-theory] The input would be represented by a large multidimensional vector whose elements represent pixels in the picture.
[src:computational-learning/statistical-learning-theory] After learning a function based on the training set data, that function is validated on a test set of data, data that did not appear in the training set.
[src:computational-learning/statistical-learning-theory] Take X to be the vector space of all possible inputs, and Y to be the vector space of all possible outputs.
[src:computational-learning/statistical-learning-theory] Statistical learning theory takes the perspective that there is some unknown probability distribution over the product space $Z=X\times Y$ , i.e. there exists some unknown $p(z)=p(\mathbf {x} ,y)$ .
[src:computational-learning/statistical-learning-theory] In this formalism, the inference problem consists of finding a function $f:X\to Y$ such that $f(\mathbf {x} )\sim y$ .
[src:computational-learning/statistical-learning-theory] Let ${\mathcal {H}}$ be a space of functions $f:X\to Y$ called the hypothesis space.
[src:computational-learning/statistical-learning-theory] The hypothesis space is the space of functions the algorithm will search through.
[src:computational-learning/statistical-learning-theory] Let $V(f(\mathbf {x} ),y)$ be the loss function, a metric for the difference between the predicted value $f(\mathbf {x} )$ and the actual value y .
[src:computational-learning/statistical-learning-theory] Because the probability distribution $p(\mathbf {x} ,y)$ is unknown, a proxy measure for the expected risk must be used.
[src:computational-learning/statistical-learning-theory] This measure is based on the training set, a sample from this unknown probability distribution.
[src:computational-learning/statistical-learning-theory] It is called the empirical risk $I_{S}[f]={\frac {1}{n}}\sum _{i=1}^{n}V(f(\mathbf {x} _{i}),y_{i})$ A learning algorithm that chooses the function $f_{S}$ that minimizes the empirical risk is called empirical risk minimization.
[src:computational-learning/statistical-learning-theory] The choice of loss function is a determining factor on the function $f_{S}$ that will be chosen by the learning algorithm.
[src:computational-learning/statistical-learning-theory] The loss function also affects the convergence rate for an algorithm.
[src:computational-learning/statistical-learning-theory] It is important for the loss function to be convex.
[src:computational-learning/statistical-learning-theory] Different loss functions are used depending on whether the problem is one of regression or one of classification.
[src:computational-learning/statistical-learning-theory] The most common loss function for regression is the square loss function (also known as the L2-norm).
[src:computational-learning/statistical-learning-theory] This familiar loss function is used in Ordinary Least Squares regression.
[src:computational-learning/statistical-learning-theory] In some sense the 0-1 indicator function is the most natural loss function for classification.
[src:computational-learning/statistical-learning-theory] It takes the value 0 if the predicted output is the same as the actual output, and it takes the value 1 if the predicted output is different from the actual output.
[src:computational-learning/statistical-learning-theory] For binary classification with $Y=\{-1,1\}$ , this is: $V(f(\mathbf {x} ),y)=\theta (-yf(\mathbf {x} ))$ where $\theta$ is the Heaviside step function.
[src:computational-learning/statistical-learning-theory] In machine learning problems, a major problem that arises is that of overfitting.
[src:computational-learning/statistical-learning-theory] Because learning is a prediction problem, the goal is not to find a function that most closely fits the (previously observed) data, but to find one that will most accurately predict output from future input.
[src:computational-learning/statistical-learning-theory] Empirical risk minimization runs this risk of overfitting: finding a function that matches the data exactly but does not predict future output well.
[src:computational-learning/statistical-learning-theory] Overfitting is symptomatic of unstable solutions; a small perturbation in the training set data would cause a large variation in the learned function.
[src:computational-learning/statistical-learning-theory] It can be shown that if the stability for the solution can be guaranteed, generalization and consistency are guaranteed as well.
[src:computational-learning/statistical-learning-theory] Regularization can solve the overfitting problem and give the problem stability.
[src:computational-learning/statistical-learning-theory] Regularization can be accomplished by restricting the hypothesis space ${\mathcal {H}}$ .
[src:computational-learning/statistical-learning-theory] A common example would be restricting ${\mathcal {H}}$ to linear functions: this can be seen as a reduction to the standard problem of linear regression. ${\mathcal {H}}$ could also be restricted to polynomial of degree p , exponentials, or bounded functions on L1.
[src:computational-learning/statistical-learning-theory] Restriction of the hypothesis space avoids overfitting because the form of the potential functions are limited, and so does not allow for the choice of a function that gives empirical risk arbitrarily close to zero.
[src:computational-learning/statistical-learning-theory] One example of regularization is Tikhonov regularization.
[src:computational-learning/statistical-learning-theory] This consists of minimizing ${\frac {1}{n}}\sum _{i=1}^{n}V(f(\mathbf {x} _{i}),y_{i})+\gamma \left\|f\right\|_{\mathcal {H}}^{2}$ where $\gamma$ is a fixed and positive parameter, the regularization parameter.
[src:computational-learning/statistical-learning-theory] Tikhonov regularization ensures existence, uniqueness, and stability of the solution.
[src:computational-learning/statistical-learning-theory] The exponential term comes from Hoeffding but there is an extra cost of taking the supremum over the whole class, which is the shattering number.
[src:computational-learning/structural-risk-minimization] Minimizing $H(W)$ in effect limits the capacity of the accessible subsets of the parameter space, thereby controlling the trade-off between minimizing the training error and minimizing the expected gap between the training error and test error.
[src:computational-learning/structural-risk-minimization] The SRM problem can be formulated in terms of data.
[src:computational-learning/structural-risk-minimization] The first term is the mean squared error (MSE) term between the value of the learned model, $h_{\theta }$ , and the given labels y .
[src:computational-learning/structural-risk-minimization] This term is the training error, $E_{train}$ , that was discussed earlier.
[src:computational-learning/structural-risk-minimization] The second term, places a prior over the weights, to favor sparsity and penalize larger weights.
[src:computational-learning/structural-risk-minimization] The trade-off coefficient, $\lambda$ , is a hyperparameter that places more or less importance on the regularization term.
[src:computational-learning/structural-risk-minimization] Larger $\lambda$ encourages sparser weights at the expense of a more optimal MSE, and smaller $\lambda$ relaxes regularization allowing the model to fit to data.
[src:computational-learning/structural-risk-minimization] Note that as $\lambda \to \infty$ the weights become zero, and as $\lambda \to 0$ , the model typically suffers from overfitting.
[src:computational-learning/version-space-learning] (i.e., one or more of hypotheses 1 through n are true).
[src:computational-learning/version-space-learning] A version space learning algorithm is presented with examples, which it will use to restrict its hypothesis space; for each example x, the hypotheses that are inconsistent with x are removed from the space.
[src:computational-learning/version-space-learning] This iterative refining of the hypothesis space is called the **candidate elimination** algorithm, the hypothesis space maintained inside the algorithm, its *version space*.
[src:computational-learning/version-space-learning] In settings where there is a generality-ordering on hypotheses, it is possible to represent the version space by two sets of hypotheses: (1) the **most specific** consistent hypotheses, and (2) the **most general** consistent hypotheses, where "consistent" indicates agreement with observed data.
[src:computational-learning/version-space-learning] The most specific hypotheses (i.e., the specific boundary **SB**) cover the observed positive training examples, and as little of the remaining feature space as possible.
[src:computational-learning/version-space-learning] These hypotheses, if reduced any further, *exclude* a *positive* training example, and hence become inconsistent.
[src:computational-learning/version-space-learning] These minimal hypotheses essentially constitute a (pessimistic) claim that the true concept is defined just by the *positive* data already observed: Thus, if a novel (never-before-seen) data point is observed, it should be assumed to be negative.
[src:computational-learning/version-space-learning] The most general hypotheses (i.e., the general boundary **GB**) cover the observed positive training examples, but also cover as much of the remaining feature space without including any negative training examples.
[src:computational-learning/version-space-learning] These, if enlarged any further, *include* a *negative* training example, and hence become inconsistent.
[src:computational-learning/version-space-learning] These maximal hypotheses essentially constitute a (optimistic) claim that the true concept is defined just by the *negative* data already observed: Thus, if a novel (never-before-seen) data point is observed, it should be assumed to be positive.
[src:computational-learning/version-space-learning] After learning, classification can be performed on unseen examples by testing the hypothesis learned by the algorithm.
[src:computational-learning/version-space-learning] If the example is consistent with multiple hypotheses, a majority vote rule can be applied.
[src:computational-learning/version-space-learning] The notion of version spaces was introduced by Mitchell in the early 1980s as a framework for understanding the basic problem of supervised learning within the context of solution search.
[src:computational-learning/version-space-learning] Although the basic "**candidate elimination**" search method that accompanies the version space framework is not a popular learning algorithm, there are some practical implementations that have been developed (e.g., Sverdlik & Reynolds 1992, Hong & Tsang 1997, Dubois & Quafafou 2002).
[src:computational-learning/version-space-learning] A major drawback of version space learning is its inability to deal with noise: any pair of inconsistent examples can cause the version space to *collapse*, i.e., become empty, so that classification becomes impossible.
[src:computational-learning/version-space-learning] One solution of this problem is proposed by Dubois and Quafafou that proposed the Rough Version Space, where rough sets based approximations are used to learn certain and possible hypothesis in the presence of inconsistent data.
[src:computational-learning/winnow-algorithm] The **winnow algorithm** is a technique from machine learning for learning a linear classifier from labeled examples.
[src:computational-learning/winnow-algorithm] It is very similar to the perceptron algorithm.
[src:computational-learning/winnow-algorithm] However, the perceptron algorithm uses an additive weight-update scheme, while Winnow uses a multiplicative scheme that allows it to perform much better when many dimensions are irrelevant (hence its name winnow).
[src:computational-learning/winnow-algorithm] It is a simple algorithm that scales well to high-dimensional data.
[src:computational-learning/winnow-algorithm] During training, Winnow is shown a sequence of positive and negative examples.
[src:computational-learning/winnow-algorithm] From these it learns a decision hyperplane that can then be used to label novel examples as positive or negative.
[src:computational-learning/winnow-algorithm] The algorithm can also be used in the online learning setting, where the learning and the classification phase are not clearly separated.
[src:computational-learning/winnow-algorithm] The basic algorithm, Winnow1, is as follows.
[src:computational-learning/winnow-algorithm] The instance space is $X=\{0,1\}^{n}$ , that is, each instance is described as a set of Boolean-valued features.
[src:computational-learning/winnow-algorithm] The algorithm maintains non-negative weights $w_{i}$ for $i\in \{1,\ldots ,n\}$ , which are initially set to 1, one weight for each feature.
[src:computational-learning/winnow-algorithm] Here $\Theta$ is a real number that is called the *threshold*.
[src:computational-learning/winnow-algorithm] Together with the weights, the threshold defines a dividing hyperplane in the instance space.
[src:computational-learning/winnow-algorithm] Good bounds are obtained if $\Theta =n/2$ (see below).
[src:computational-learning/winnow-algorithm] There are many variations to this basic approach.
[src:computational-learning/winnow-algorithm] *Winnow2* is similar except that in the demotion step the weights are divided by α instead of being set to 0.
[src:computational-learning/winnow-algorithm] *Balanced Winnow* maintains two sets of weights, and thus two hyperplanes.
[src:computational-learning/winnow-algorithm] This can then be generalized for multi-label classification.
[src:computational-learning/winnow-algorithm] In certain circumstances, it can be shown that the number of mistakes Winnow makes as it learns has an upper bound that is independent of the number of instances with which it is presented.
